00:00:00.700 --> 00:00:02.920
PROFESSOR: One of
the things you will

00:00:02.920 --> 00:00:05.080
be thinking about
in the homework

00:00:05.080 --> 00:00:10.060
is the definition of
gauge-invariant observables.

00:00:10.060 --> 00:00:16.720
So an operator O is a
gauge-invariant observable--

00:00:20.400 --> 00:00:29.880
gauge environment
observable-- if, see,

00:00:29.880 --> 00:00:35.120
under a gauged
transformation, O can change.

00:00:35.120 --> 00:00:39.380
The operator can change under
a gauged transformation.

00:00:39.380 --> 00:00:42.310
You'd say, oh, but isn't it
supposed to be gauge-invariant?

00:00:42.310 --> 00:00:45.980
But, well, it's not
quite the operator itself

00:00:45.980 --> 00:00:48.080
that is gauge-invariant.

00:00:48.080 --> 00:00:50.410
It is its expectation value.

00:00:50.410 --> 00:00:56.570
So you should have that
psi prime of O prime psi

00:00:56.570 --> 00:01:05.000
prime is equal to psi O psi.

00:01:05.000 --> 00:01:07.830
So the operator may change.

00:01:07.830 --> 00:01:10.520
And that's OK.

00:01:10.520 --> 00:01:13.530
The wave function
will change as well.

00:01:13.530 --> 00:01:16.850
So the question is that
if you put the new wave

00:01:16.850 --> 00:01:20.090
function and the new operator
and you find the expectation

00:01:20.090 --> 00:01:22.620
value, do you get
the same thing?

00:01:22.620 --> 00:01:24.890
That's what you really can ask.

00:01:24.890 --> 00:01:27.890
You cannot ask more than that.

00:01:27.890 --> 00:01:32.580
And you will see very funny
things when you do this.

00:01:32.580 --> 00:01:37.640
You will see that
this operator, P,

00:01:37.640 --> 00:01:40.730
the momentum operator
that you like,

00:01:40.730 --> 00:01:46.200
that you find has been
intuitive for you so far,

00:01:46.200 --> 00:01:49.970
is not gauge-invariant.

00:01:49.970 --> 00:01:52.880
You cannot compute the
expectation value of it

00:01:52.880 --> 00:01:55.440
and expect something physical.

00:01:55.440 --> 00:02:01.150
It's not gauge-invariant.

00:02:01.150 --> 00:02:05.270
The thing that is
gauge-invariant is P minus q

00:02:05.270 --> 00:02:07.510
over c A--

00:02:07.510 --> 00:02:09.190
is gauge-invariant.

00:02:16.822 --> 00:02:20.810
So it's some small
calculations you will do.

00:02:20.810 --> 00:02:23.120
In order to get the
gauge-invariant operator,

00:02:23.120 --> 00:02:26.390
you do, in general, have
to put in a dependence.

00:02:26.390 --> 00:02:27.750
That's the funny thing.

00:02:27.750 --> 00:02:31.940
So this thing will not
be gauge-invariant.

00:02:31.940 --> 00:02:33.950
And, you know,
it's almost obvious

00:02:33.950 --> 00:02:36.500
that P is not gauge-invariant.

00:02:36.500 --> 00:02:37.310
Why?

00:02:37.310 --> 00:02:42.020
Because P, under a
gauge transformation--

00:02:42.020 --> 00:02:43.850
well, the gauge
transformation, say,

00:02:43.850 --> 00:02:48.920
change A, change phi
prime, change psi.

00:02:48.920 --> 00:02:52.940
But it doesn't say change P. So
in the gauge transformation, P

00:02:52.940 --> 00:02:55.060
goes to P.

00:02:55.060 --> 00:03:02.400
But then let's look at
psi prime P psi prime.

00:03:02.400 --> 00:03:07.880
Is it equal to psi P psi?

00:03:07.880 --> 00:03:12.270
Well, here you
have that psi prime

00:03:12.270 --> 00:03:22.580
is psi times e to the minus
i q lambda over h bar c.

00:03:22.580 --> 00:03:24.690
You have P here.

00:03:24.690 --> 00:03:31.020
And e to the i q
lambda over h bar c.

00:03:31.020 --> 00:03:34.710
Psi prime-- no, psi.

00:03:34.710 --> 00:03:36.990
That's the left-hand side.

00:03:36.990 --> 00:03:43.640
And this P is such that
