00:08:55.740 --> 00:08:56.970
We'll see.

00:08:56.970 --> 00:09:00.930
But let's put an assumption.

00:09:00.930 --> 00:09:03.990
The assumption is that we're
doing quantum mechanics,

00:09:03.990 --> 00:09:11.755
and there exists a
particle with charge.

00:09:14.410 --> 00:09:17.020
And I'll call it this time q.

00:09:17.020 --> 00:09:17.670
I'll just--

00:09:21.130 --> 00:09:24.210
So if we're doing
quantum mechanics,

00:09:24.210 --> 00:09:28.880
and there exists a
particle of charge q,

00:09:28.880 --> 00:09:34.130
I need potentials to describe
the quantum mechanics.

00:09:34.130 --> 00:09:38.180
I need an A field
to describe this.

00:09:38.180 --> 00:09:44.270
So I know B is consistent,
and it makes sense,

00:09:44.270 --> 00:09:48.020
and we can use it,
if and only if I

00:09:48.020 --> 00:09:51.800
can find a vector potential.

00:09:51.800 --> 00:09:56.230
So our task is to find a
vector potential on this torus.

00:10:07.950 --> 00:10:14.910
Well, at first sight that
doesn't sound too difficult.

00:10:14.910 --> 00:10:19.080
You can say, all right, let's
find the vector potential.

00:10:19.080 --> 00:10:26.220
That's easy to find an A such
that curl of A is equal to B.

00:10:26.220 --> 00:10:37.080
So B z is dx A y minus dy A x.

00:10:37.080 --> 00:10:39.240
So let's simplify my life.

00:10:39.240 --> 00:10:46.770
Let's take A y to
be equal to B z,

00:10:46.770 --> 00:10:54.300
and let's call this magnetic
field B0, the constant value

00:10:54.300 --> 00:10:56.030
B0.

00:10:56.030 --> 00:10:57.640
Constant.

00:10:57.640 --> 00:11:09.360
So A y would be equal to B0
times x, and A x would be 0.

00:11:09.360 --> 00:11:10.080
OK.

00:11:10.080 --> 00:11:11.040
That's it.

00:11:11.040 --> 00:11:12.930
Look.

00:11:12.930 --> 00:11:16.920
A y is equal to B0 x.

00:11:16.920 --> 00:11:19.860
So I take the
derivative dx of A y.

00:11:19.860 --> 00:11:21.300
I get B0.

00:11:21.300 --> 00:11:23.370
dy of A x is 0.

00:11:23.370 --> 00:11:24.630
Perfect.

00:11:24.630 --> 00:11:26.970
All done, we would say.

00:11:26.970 --> 00:11:30.660
You found the A y.

00:11:30.660 --> 00:11:39.150
But there is a problem with this
[? A i. ?] What is the problem?

00:11:39.150 --> 00:11:44.430
If this is a torus,
it means these points

00:11:44.430 --> 00:11:47.550
are the same as these points.

00:11:47.550 --> 00:11:52.740
So I should have,
the vector potential

00:11:52.740 --> 00:11:56.220
here must be the same as
the vector potential there.

00:11:56.220 --> 00:11:59.970
Because it is, after
all, the same point.

00:11:59.970 --> 00:12:03.000
You're gluing the surface.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:08.760
But, OK, this point and
this point differ by y.

00:12:08.760 --> 00:12:12.150
And this vector potential
doesn't depend on y.

00:12:12.150 --> 00:12:12.780
So, phew.

00:12:12.780 --> 00:12:14.190
That's good.

00:12:14.190 --> 00:12:19.560
A is well-defined because it
has the same value anywhere here

00:12:19.560 --> 00:12:21.090
as anywhere there.

00:12:21.090 --> 00:12:30.990
So I can write it as A y of
x, y plus L y at any point x.

00:12:30.990 --> 00:12:38.980
And y plus L y is the
same thing as A y of xy.

00:12:38.980 --> 00:12:40.090
So that's very good.

00:12:42.630 --> 00:12:45.450
But we're going to run
into trouble in the second

00:12:45.450 --> 00:12:52.720
now, because the A y should be
the same here and here, too.

00:12:52.720 --> 00:12:57.610
Because that's also the
same points in the torus.

00:12:57.610 --> 00:12:59.860
This line is
identified with this.

00:12:59.860 --> 00:13:07.130
So when I change x by L
x, A y should not change.

00:13:07.130 --> 00:13:18.870
And here it seems like A y at x
plus L x, and the same point y,

00:13:18.870 --> 00:13:24.640
is not the same as A y at xy.

00:13:24.640 --> 00:13:30.310
And this is a torus, so this
point, x plus L x and y and y

00:13:30.310 --> 00:13:31.820
should be the same.

00:13:31.820 --> 00:13:39.410
So this vector potential is
not the same here as here.

00:13:39.410 --> 00:13:42.760
So, actually, this vector
potential doesn't look good.

00:13:42.760 --> 00:13:47.830
You thought you could write
the magnetic field in terms

00:13:47.830 --> 00:13:50.470
of a vector potential,
but this vector potential

00:13:50.470 --> 00:13:53.620
doesn't seem to
live on the torus.

00:13:53.620 --> 00:13:56.980
It's just not a
well-defined magnetic vector

00:13:56.980 --> 00:13:58.360
potential in the torus.

00:13:58.360 --> 00:14:01.690
It doesn't have the same
value here and here.

00:14:01.690 --> 00:14:05.440
So in principle,
we're not through.

00:14:05.440 --> 00:14:07.330
We're not out of the woods here.

00:14:07.330 --> 00:14:12.130
We have not been able to find
a good vector potential yet.

00:14:14.770 --> 00:14:17.130
But here, the gauge
transformations

00:14:17.130 --> 00:14:19.220
come a little to the rescue.

00:14:22.250 --> 00:14:25.610
When you work with
vector potentials,

00:14:25.610 --> 00:14:31.130
you don't really need
that the vector potential

00:14:31.130 --> 00:14:35.600
be the same here as here.

00:14:35.600 --> 00:14:40.850
It is enough if the
vector potential here

00:14:40.850 --> 00:14:43.730
and here, which
is the same point,

00:14:43.730 --> 00:14:48.440
they differ by a
gauge transformation.

00:14:48.440 --> 00:14:51.490
So the vector potential
is a subtle object.

00:14:51.490 --> 00:14:52.540
Here is the torus.

00:14:52.540 --> 00:14:55.960
In one part of the
torus it has a formula.

00:14:55.960 --> 00:15:00.170
In the other part, it may
look like it's not consistent.

00:15:00.170 --> 00:15:02.710
But you can use
another formula related

00:15:02.710 --> 00:15:04.520
by a gauge transformation.

00:15:04.520 --> 00:15:09.970
So this vector
potential here is OK

00:15:09.970 --> 00:15:15.550
if I manage to show that
what I get on this side

00:15:15.550 --> 00:15:19.220
is just the gauge transformation
of what I was getting here.

00:15:19.220 --> 00:15:21.790
So physically
these are the same.

00:15:21.790 --> 00:15:26.230
And yes, you have a unique
configuration on the torus

00:15:26.230 --> 00:15:30.220
if the vector potential here is
gauge-equivalent to the vector

00:15:30.220 --> 00:15:33.430
potential there.

00:15:33.430 --> 00:15:35.310
So let's try to do that.

00:15:47.320 --> 00:15:50.840
So, gauge transformations
to the rescue.

00:15:50.840 --> 00:15:51.630
OK.

00:15:51.630 --> 00:15:56.700
A y of x plus Lxy.

00:15:56.700 --> 00:16:01.650
I want it to be a
gauge transformation

00:16:01.650 --> 00:16:06.930
of the field at A y xy.

00:16:06.930 --> 00:16:14.130
So remember, A prime was
